{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:47:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"296"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17577210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17577210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T03:39:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T03:39:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"296"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:47:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:47:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"296"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/296"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.1,0.12,0.53,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/296"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75770"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1418"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6088"},{"type":"tags","id":"6112"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31646"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-day-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother for review. He was delivered vaginally with a birth weight of 4510 grams following a difficult delivery with shoulder dystocia. He has no other medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right arm is held in adduction and internal rotation at the shoulder, with extension and pronation of the forearm, and flexion of the wrist. The Moro reflex is asymmetrical, being absent on the right side, though the grasp reflex is present bilaterally. The left arm has normal movement and reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C5-T1 nerve roots","C8-T1 nerve roots","Median nerve","C5-C6 nerve roots","Axillary nerve"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic \u0027waiter\u0027s tip\u0027 position characteristic of Erb\u0027s palsy, which results from injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003EC5-C6 nerve roots\u003C/strong\u003E forming the upper trunk of the brachial plexus. This typically occurs during difficult deliveries, particularly those complicated by shoulder dystocia, and is more common in macrosomic infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInjury to \u003Cstrong\u003EC5-T1 nerve roots\u003C/strong\u003E would cause complete brachial plexus palsy, resulting in a flaccid arm with absent grasp reflex and often associated Horner\u0027s syndrome, which is not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInjury to \u003Cstrong\u003EC8-T1 nerve roots\u003C/strong\u003E (Klumpke\u0027s palsy) causes lower trunk paralysis, affecting intrinsic hand muscles and presenting with a claw hand deformity. This is a rare form of neonatal brachial plexus injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would primarily affect forearm pronation and wrist/finger flexion but would not cause the shoulder positioning seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury alone would only affect shoulder abduction via the deltoid muscle and would not explain the forearm and wrist positioning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe prognosis of Erb\u0027s palsy is generally good, with most cases recovering spontaneously within the first few months of life. However, early referral for physiotherapy is important, and some cases may require surgical intervention if there is no improvement by 3-6 months of age.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erb\u0027s palsy presents with the \u0027waiter\u0027s tip\u0027 position: shoulder adducted and internally rotated, extended elbow, and flexed wrist.","Upper trunk (C5-C6) brachial plexus injury is the most common neonatal brachial plexus injury, typically associated with shoulder dystocia.","Macrosomia is a risk factor for brachial plexus injury during delivery."],"references":["Executive summary: neonatal brachial plexus palsy. American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists.\u00a0Obstet Gynecol\u00a02014;123:902\u2013904. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24785634/","Heise C, Martins R, Siqueira M. Neonatal brachial plexus palsy: a permanent challenge.\u00a0Arg Neuro-Psiquiatr. 2015; 73(9). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26352501/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"296"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T20:29:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T20:29:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"296"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92458"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":nu